Self-Attention In Computer Vision

Branislav Holländer

Sep 25, 2019·10 min read

Ever since the introduction of Transformer networks, the attention mechanism in deep learning has enjoyed great popularity in the machine translation as well as NLP communities. However, in computer vision, convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are still the norm and self-attention just began to slowly creep into the main body of research, either complementing existing CNN architectures or completely replacing them. In this post I will try to illuminate recent developments in visual self-attention and highlight its possible benefits. For this task, I will present three different papers (including one that was accepted for the upcoming NeurIPS 2019 conference) which in my opinion illustrate the state-of-the-art of self-attention in computer vision very well.

The first paper I will present by Guan et al. [1] comes from the medical image analysis community, which is where I feel at home. Unlike natural images (photographs), medical images are often quite similar in their appearance. They are acquired using similar acquisition parameters from standardized positions. For radiologists, the experience in reading the images comes mostly from knowing where exactly to look in order to find a certain pathology. Therefore it is not surprising that attention played a big role in medical image analysis even before other research areas.

The paper in question tries to improve the performance of automated thorax disease classification on chest X-ray images. Previously, networks have been proposed that detect and classify pathologies on chest X-ray by just looking at the global image. Hereby, multilabel classification is performed by either using binary cross entropy (BCE) as a loss function or some other labeling mechanism (e.g. encoder-decoder framework using LSTM as a decoder to capture mutual dependencies between the labels [2]). The problem with using the entire X-ray image for classification is that in medical images, the lesion area may be very small compared to the entire image and may even be located somewhere along the borders, causing a great amount of noise for the classifier and lowering detection accuracy. Furthermore, chest X-ray images often suffer from misalignment (such as the example in Figure 1, second row). This misalignment causes irregular borders around the image and may also negatively impact classification.

In the paper, the authors use recursive hard attention (i.e. hard self-attention) to improve the detection accuracy by cropping out the discriminative parts of the image and classifying both the global image as well as the cropped portion together (see Figure 1 for the entire image on the left side and the cropped part on the right).

The network consists of three branches:

  • Global branch processing the entire image and determining the cropping ROI,
  • Local branch exhibiting the attention mechanism and processing the cropped image,
  • Fusion branch concatenating the pooling outputs of the global and local branches and performing final classification using dense layers.

All branches are classification networks that perform multiclass classification at the end (as can be seen in Figure 2) to predict the presence of pathologies. In addition to the classification, the global branch is used to generate the heatmap which determines the cropped region. The heatmap is generated by counting the maximum values along channels at a certain high-level layer. Then a mask is generated with the same size as the heatmap. If the value of the per-channel maximized heatmap at a certain position (x,y) is larger than some threshold, the mask is assigned 1 at that position. Otherwise, the mask will have the value 0. Afterwards, the cropping area is determined so that all the points with mask value 1 are inside the cropping. Then the cropped part of the image is run through the local branch. Additionally, the outputs of both branches are fused in the fusion branch to perform an additional classification.

The network is trained in three steps:

  • Fine-tuning of the global branch pretrained by ImageNet.
  • Mask inference to obtain the cropped images and perform fine-tuning of the local branch. Hereby, the weights in the global branch are fixed.
  • Concatenating of the global and local branch outputs and fine-tuning of the fusion branch while freezing the weights of the other branches.

The fusion branch is used to produce the final classification results of the model, as it performs better than the other two branches, as expected.

In order to understand what the model is doing from an attention point-of-view we have to first know the difference between soft and hard attention. In essence, attention reweighs certain features of the network according to some externally or internally (self-attention) supplied weights. Hereby, soft attention allows these weights to be continuous while hard attention requires them to be binary, i.e. 0 or 1. This model is an example of hard attention because it crops a certain part of the image, hereby essentially reweighing the original so that the cropped part has weight 1 and the rest 0.

The main drawback of hard attention is that it is not differentiable and cannot be trained end-to-end. Instead, the authors use the activations of a certain layer to determine the ROI and train the network in a complicated multi-stage process. In order to train the attention gates, we have to use soft attention (e.g. using sigmoid or softmax). We will have a look at some soft-attention models next.

Squeeze-And-Excitation-Networks

Instead of using hard attention and recalibrating the weights in terms of cropping of the feature maps, Hu et al. [3] looked at reweighting the channel-wise responses in a certain layer of a CNN by using soft self-attention to model inter-dependencies between the channels of the convolutional features. For this purpose, the authors introduce the Squeeze-And-Excitation building block (see Figure 3).

The Squeeze-And-Excitation block works as follows: for any transformation of features F_tr from X to U (e.g. convolution), there is a transformation F_sq that aggregates the global feature responses across spatial extents (H, W). This is the squeeze operation. The squeeze operation is followed by the excitation operation F_ex, which is a self-gating operation that constructs a channel-wise weight response. The output of F_tr is subsequently multiplied channel-wise by the result of the excitation (this is depicted as F_scale in Figure 3). The mathematical description of the Squeeze operation is

Hereby u_c are the outputs of the operation F_tr. The squeeze operation creates a global embedding by using global average pooling. Global max pooling could also be used, although the authors note that average pooling increases the overall performance slightly. The excitation block on the other hand is described by

The excitation thus multiplies the output of the squeeze block by learned weights W1, passes the output through the ReLU function δ, mutliplies the output by another set of weights W2 and uses a sigmoid function at the end to ensure that the resulting channel weights are positive. Hereby, W1 reduces the dimensionality by the factor r (which can be regarded as a hyperparameter), whereas W2 increases it again to the original number of channels. Finally, the channel feature responses of F_tr are multiplied by the weights obtained from the excitation block. This can be viewed as a self-attention function on the channels using global information.

The main idea behind the Squeeze-And-Excitation block is to include global information in the decision process of the network; whereas convolution only looks at local spatial information in a certain radius, the Squeeze-And-Excitation block aggregates the information from the entire receptive field. An interesting observation of the authors is that the excitation weights are relatively similar for different classes in the earlier stage of the network and become more specific in later stages. This correlates with the usual assumption that lower layers learn more general features of the input while higher layers are increasingly discriminative. Additionally, the Squeeze-And-Excitation block does not make much sense at the last stage of the network, where most excitations become 1. This can be explained by the fact that the last stage of the network already contains most of the global information and there is no new information content brought in by the Squeeze-And-Excitation operation.

The main advantage of the Squeeze-And-Excitation approach is that it is very flexible: the authors mention the integration in widely-used architectures such as ResNet (see Figure 4), Inception or ResNeXt. In practice, the block could either be added to every stage of the network or just at particular stages. Furthermore, it introduces only a slight overhead in terms of the number of learnable parameters. For example the SE-ResNet-50 using the Squeeze-And-Excitation block only uses ~2.5 million additional parameters compared to the original ResNet, which already contains 25 million parameters. Thus, this constitutes only a 10% increase in complexity.

In the paper, the authors present a great number of examples of training architectures enhanced by the Squeeze-And-Excitation block. In particular, they were able to achieve state-of-the-art classification performance in the ILSVRC 2017 challenge, reaching a top-5 error of just 2.251%.

Stand-Alone Self-Attention

The last article I will present, a NeurIPS 2019 submission, takes the idea of self-attention in CNNs even further by using stand-alone self-attention blocks instead of only enhancing convolutional layers by self-attention. In fact, the authors present a self-attention layer which may be used to replace convolution while reducing the number of parameters.

Let’s review the convolution operation to motivate the replacement. Convolution operations consist of multiplying a weight matrix of a certain size (e.g. 3x3) with every neighborhood at position (i,j) and summing the result spatially. This enables weight sharing between different spatial positions. Furthermore, the number of weights is independent of the input size.

Similarly to convolution, the self-attention layer proposed by the paper also works on a small neighborhood around (i,j), which is referred to as a memory block. For every memory block, the single-headed attention is then computed as follows:

Hereby, q_ij=W_q x_ij are the queries, k_ab=W_k x_ab the keys and v_ab=W_v x_ab the values computed as linear transformations from the features at position (i,j) and its neighborhood. The matrices W are learned transformations. As you can see from the formula, the transformed center pixel x_ij functions as the query, with the keys and values being summed over the neighborhood. A softmax function is also applied to the logits to obtain the weights which are then multiplied by the values. If you don’t know what queries, keys and values are, take a look at this article. The authors use multiheaded attention in this article, which simply means that the pixel features are split depthwise into N groups of the same size, the attention is computed on each group individually with different matrices W and the results are concatenated. Figure 6 provides a graphical description of the visual self-attention block.

One issue with using the approach described above is that there is no positional information encoded in the attention block and thus the formula is invariant to permutations of the individual pixels. Positional information is important for vision tasks: if you want to detect a human face for instance, you will need to know where to look for the mouth, the nose, the ears etc. In the original transformer paper [5], the authors use sinusoidal embeddings for the position as an additional input. In [4], however, relative 2D position embeddings are used due to their better accuracy for computer vision tasks. These relative embeddings are obtained by calculating the relative distances of the position (i,j) to every neighborhood pixel (a,b). These distances are split up into row and column distances r_a-i and r_b-j. These embeddings are concatenated to a matrix form and multiplied by the query q_ij as follows:

This makes sure that the weights computed by the softmax function are modulated by the distance and content of the key and the query.

As we can see from the description above, visual self-attention is a form of local attention. The attention layer only focuses on the memory block instead of the whole feature map. The advantage of this approach is that the number of parameters is drastically reduced and the weights between different spatial positions are shared. The authors mention that their self-attention networks are still slower in training and inference than their CNN counterparts, however they attribute this to the highly optimized convolutional kernels as well as a lack of optimized hardware for the attention layer.

The authors also present some results which they obtained on ImageNet by replacing the 3x3 convolution in a ResNet by their self-attention block. Notice that they leave the 1x1 convolutions (which are basically fully-connected layers calculated per-pixel) and the convolutional stem (the first few convolutional layers in the network untouched. With these changes in place, they outperform the baseline (standard ResNet) in all tested architectures (ResNet-26, ResNet-38 and ResNet-50) while using 12% fewer FLOPS and 29% fewer parameters.

References

[1] Guan, Qingji, et al. “Diagnose like a radiologist: Attention guided convolutional neural network for thorax disease classification.” arXiv preprint arXiv:1801.09927 (2018).

[2] Yao, Li, et al. “Learning to diagnose from scratch by exploiting dependencies among labels.” arXiv preprint arXiv:1710.10501 (2017).

[3] Hu, Jie, Li Shen, and Gang Sun. “Squeeze-and-excitation networks.” Proceedings of the IEEE conference on computer vision and pattern recognition. 2018.

[4] Ramachandran, Prajit, et al. “Stand-Alone Self-Attention in Vision Models.” arXiv preprint arXiv:1906.05909 (2019).

[5] Vaswani, Ashish, et al. “Attention is all you need.” Advances in neural information processing systems. 2017.
